    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-08-15T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-08-15T05:00:00-05:00" n="843"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d843">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/14012: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Beirut</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Engert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Beirut</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-08-15T12:00:00+02:00"
                            >August 15, 1941—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 10:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>333. Exchange of letters mentioned in my telegram 332, August 15, 11 a.m., was
                    the outcome of recent conversations between Lyttelton and de Gaulle in Beirut in
                    order to convince the latter of the good faith of the British Government and if
                    possible to prevent further reckless observations such as he made to me on
                    August 5 and reported in my 323.<note n="38" xml:id="d843fn38">Dated August 5,
                        11 p.m., <ref target="#pg_780">p. 780</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>It may amuse the Department to learn that General Wilson claims he found de
                    Gaulle much more reasonable and tractable after I had my chat with him but I
                    doubt whether the present extraordinary <pb facs="0791" n="783" xml:id="pg_783"
                    /> complexity of the daily contacts between the British and French political and
                    military authorities in the Levant States can in the near future be expected to
                    become less acute.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
